         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">My dear Sir ¶  ¶ As soon as I received the last box of Leguminosae in the beginning of last month I set about revising the Papilionaceae down to Hedysareae with your specimens and have now packed and ...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">64.02.25a</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">From George Bentham</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RB MSS M4, Library, Royal Botanic Gardens Melbourne.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">My dear Sir</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>As soon as I received the last box of <name key="Leguminosae">Leguminosae</name> in the beginning of last month I set about revising the <name key="Papilionaceae">Papilionaceae</name> down to <name key="Hedysareae">Hedysareae</name> with your specimens and have now packed and sent off two boxes per "Suffolk" and hope to enclose the bill of lading — This took me above a month — much longer than I expected. The Oxylobiums <name key="Gastrolobium">Gastrolobium</name>s <name key="Mirbelia">Mirbelia</name>s and <name key="Chorizema">Chorizema</name>s were much mixed and I had to examine the ovaries of a great many specimens — but I remained further convinced that these genera connected as they are must be kept up. <name key="Chorizema">Chorizema</name> appears to me to be readily distinguished by the keel — <name key="Mirbelia">Mirbelia</name>s are sometimes more difficult to separate from Oxylobium, and <name key="Gastrolobium">Gastrolobium</name>s can often only be determined by soaking the ovary. I had also a great deal of trouble again with <name key="Pultenaea">Pultenaea</name>s and Swainsonas — among the latter specimens that have not fruit as well as flower must often remain doubtful — some from Ridley's<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See J. B. Ridley's account of his expedition from Nicol Bay to the De Grey River, WA, <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Inquirer and commercial news</seg> (Perth), 30 September 1863, p. 3.</p>
               </note> Expedition to Nickol Bay &amp; De Grey river in flower and fruit show that <name key="Diplolobium%20Walcottii">Diplolobium Walcottii</name> is identical with S. occidentalis.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>With your letter of Decr just received<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See M to G. Bentham, 12 December 1863.</p>
               </note> were some specimens of "<name key="Oxylobium%20elachophyllum">Oxylobium elachophyllum</name>" this is O. hamulosum A. Gray Bot. Amer. Expl. Exped.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">A. Gray (1854). See also Bentham's annotation on M to G. Bentham, 12 December 1863, n. 33. </p>
               </note> a species closely allied to and perhaps not distinct from O. <name key="Pultenaea">Pultenaea</name>e DC. The latter is not in your herbarium — the one you mistook for it (<name key="Chorizema%20Pultenaeae">Chorizema Pultenaeae</name> F. Muell) is <name key="Chorizema%20parviflorum">Chorizema parviflorum</name> Benth in Ann Wien. Mus.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Bentham (1837), p. 71.</p>
               </note> — your <name key="Chorizema%20Leichhardtii">Chorizema Leichhardtii</name> is my <name key="Isotropis%20filicaulis">Isotropis filicaulis</name> Benth in Ann Wien Mus<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Bentham (1837), p. 71.</p>
               </note> very nearly allied to but distinct from your <name key="Isotropis%20Wheeleri">Isotropis Wheeleri</name> — I fear I must suppress also your <name key="Psoralea%20Leichhardtii">Psoralea Leichhardtii</name> which is the Indian <name key="Indigofera%20glandulosa">Indigofera glandulosa</name>. There are always 2 ovules, at least, the pod is at length 2-valved and the anthers are those of Indogofera not of Psoralea.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I am glad to hear you have obtained Steetz's herbarium<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See M to G. Bentham, 12 December 1863, and also Short &amp; Sinkora (1988).</p>
               </note> as I have no doubt there is much in it authentically named — and his set of Preiss's plants is I dare to say as good as any — Sonder's is nearly complete and without it I should never have guessed at such species as for instance Steudel's Steetz was not always quite accurate in his deteminations but yet much more so than many others who worked at Preiss's plants</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The two boxes sent contain all the <name key="Podalyrieae">Podalyrieae</name> except two or three parcels which were put to go but which would not go into the boxes — I have enough ready to fill another box but as you did not wish too many to go by the same vessel I keep them for next time.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have just done <name key="Phaseoleae">Phaseoleae</name> — then <name key="Dalbergieae">Dalbergieae</name> are pretty well done for Genera and there are not above 2 or 3 Australian species and I think I shall only do the Australian <name key="Caesalpinieae">Caesalpinieae</name> so as to get as soon as possible to Acacia As soon as <name key="Leguminosae">Leguminosae</name> are done I shall commence printing.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>With regard to keeping up <name key="Eugenia">Eugenia</name> as Wight proposed<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See M to G. Bentham, 12 December 1863. Wight (1840-53), vol. 2, pp 12-18, proposed using several sub-genera.</p>
               </note> I do not know how it can be done taking the American ones into account O. Berg<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See, for example, O. Berg (1857-59), pp. 214-326.</p>
               </note> has published between 400 &amp; 500 Brasilian <name key="Eugenia">Eugenia</name>s in the most restricted sense — and I believe that half of them at least are good species.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I can assure you that all your plants are kept perfectly dry in the rooms in which I work — they are packed to return to you in the Herbarium and do not go at all to the tinsman's shop nor out of the house — which is perfectly dry — till they are soldered up and closed when they are taken at once to the shipping agent's.<note xml:id="ftn9" type="footnote" n="9">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See M to G. Bentham, 12 December 1863.</p>
               </note> I trust you will receive what are now sent in good order.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have kept up your <name key="Oxylobium%20alpestre">Oxylobium alpestre</name> though with some hesitation — most of the specimens so marked which you first sent were the true O. ellipticum as you afterwards corrected them in your herbarium — and the two are certainly very much alike.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Maxwell's last plants from the eastward of Cape Riche are certainly very good — but most of them were already in Drummond's and Baxter's<note xml:id="ftn10" type="footnote" n="10">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">i.e. James Drummond (1784-1863); William Baxter <seg style="font-style: italic; ">fl</seg>. 1820s-1830s. </p>
               </note> collections who both of them must have gone some way to the Eastward — this however gives you many of Turczaninow's — he published above 50 of Drummond's <name key="Papilionaceae">Papilionaceae</name>.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Ever yours sincerely</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>George Bentham</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Febr 25/64</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The bill of lading is I believe sent to you direct from Kew </p>
